<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many kilometers is 1 degree of latitude?", answer: "One degree of latitude is approximately 111.32 kilometers everywhere on Earth, because lines of latitude are evenly spaced from pole to pole. The value is very slightly different between the equator (~110.57 km) and the poles (~111.69 km) because Earth is an oblate spheroid rather than a perfect sphere, but for most practical uses the constant 111.32 km is used. This value makes latitude conveniently predictable — 0.01 degrees is always about 1.1 km." },
  { question: "How many kilometers is 1 degree of longitude?", answer: "Unlike latitude, one degree of longitude varies with latitude because lines of longitude converge at the poles. At the equator, 1 degree of longitude is about 111.32 km, the same as latitude. At 45 degrees latitude, it shrinks to about 78.7 km (111.32 × cos(45°)). At 60 degrees latitude, it is about 55.7 km. Right at the pole, it is 0 km — all meridians meet at a single point. This is why the east-west extent of geographic grids stretches as you move toward the equator on a Mercator map." },
  { question: "When would I use this calculator?", answer: "This calculator is useful any time you need to convert between angular coordinates and ground distance. GPS precision specifications use both units (4 decimal places of latitude ≈ 11 meters; 5 decimal places ≈ 1.1 meters). GIS users compute pixel spacing for rasters and tile grids. Map makers estimate scale and coverage. Drone pilots figure out how much ground a given flight plan will cover. And geographic educators use it to explain why Mercator maps distort area so badly." },
  { question: "Is Earth really a sphere?", answer: "Earth is an oblate spheroid — a sphere flattened slightly at the poles and bulging at the equator. The WGS-84 reference ellipsoid used by GPS has an equatorial radius of 6378 km and a polar radius of 6357 km, a difference of 21 km or about 0.3 percent. For everyday coordinate conversions this calculator uses a spherical model with a mean radius of 6371 km (or 111.32 km per degree of latitude), which is accurate to better than 0.5 percent for almost all practical uses." },
  { question: "How does this relate to GPS accuracy?", answer: "If your GPS reports coordinates with 5 decimal places of precision, that is roughly 1.1 meters of horizontal precision along latitude and about 1.1 × cos(latitude) meters along longitude. Six decimal places give roughly 11 cm precision, which is finer than most consumer GPS can actually achieve. The precision of the number on the screen is different from the accuracy of the measurement — which depends on satellite geometry, atmospheric conditions, and device quality." }
]) %>

